{"title_page": "Woodhall Spa", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country                  = England\n|official_name            = Woodhall Spa\n|static_image_name        = Kinema in the Woods.jpg\n|static_image_caption     = Kinema in the Woods\n|coordinates              = {{coord|53.1515|-0.2183|display=inline,title}}\n|os_grid_reference        = TF196631\n| population              = 4,003\n| population_density_km2  =\n| population_ref          = (Including Kirkstead. 2011)<ref>Census, 2011</ref>\n|shire_district           = [[East Lindsey]]\n| shire_county            = [[Lincolnshire]]\n|region                   = East Midlands\n|constituency_westminster = [[Louth and Horncastle (UK Parliament constituency)|Louth and Horncastle]]\n|post_town                = WOODHALL SPA\n|postcode_district        = LN10\n|postcode_area            = LN\n|dial_code                = 01526\n|london_distance_mi       = 115<!-- straight line per MOS \u2013 constant and comparable with other place distances -->\n|london_direction         = S\n|area_total_km2           = 13.42\n}}\n'''Woodhall Spa''' is a former spa town and civil parish in [[Lincolnshire]], England, on the southern edge of the [[Lincolnshire Wolds]], {{convert|6|mi|km|0}} south-west of [[Horncastle, Lincolnshire|Horncastle]], {{convert|23|mi|km}} west of [[Skegness]], {{convert|15|mi|km}} east-south-east of [[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]] and {{convert|17|mi|km|0}} north-west of [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]]. It is noted for its [[mineral springs]], [[The Kinema in the Woods|cinema]] and its [[Second World War]] association with the [[RAF]] [[No. 617 Squadron RAF#Second World War|617 Squadron]]. The cinema has the last remaining rear screen projector in the country.\n\nMuch of the village's [[Victorian era|Victorian]] elegance remains, and since January 1991 much of the centre has been a designated [[conservation area]].<ref name=Cons>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:Xcf5GGuKZjwJ:www.e-lindsey.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/3C7DD823-9CC3-48F0-9194-66C3EFE9C1F7/0/woodhall_spa_conservation_area_appraisal_draft.pdf+woodhall+spa+well+collapsed&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjU-7m8sFcm55NM6F9EBXE41ErZPP8hQfATJ-m7TfEjdjQ9Bt3axe-mYkT5FOqNlX0aPQpuask3qAejS1qvNovpj8LoQGf8j9GrKYORCtc7UEKKOm6LSaTUUqPVWgCb5hdY5Szn&sig=AHIEtbTc1krGEJuLtHkPys0HjQ6k69L8MA|publisher=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area Appraisal|page= 5|accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Ancient history===\nA [[mesolithic]] flint blade and a [[neolithic]] stone axe have been found in Woodhall. From the [[Bronze Age]] there is a dagger and a barrow. A [[medieval]] guildhall has been excavated.<ref>[https://www.digital-documents.co.uk/cgi-bin/web-archi.pl?ARCHIFormNGRLetter=TF&ARCHIFormNGR_x=19&ARCHIFormNGR_y=63&password=freesearch@freesearch.com&TownName=WOODHALL%20SPA&county=Lincolnshire&distance=10000&period=&font_size=&placename=Woodhall%20Spa&info2search4=archi_town_search&keywords= Archi UK]</ref>\n\n===Development===\nWoodhall Spa came about by accident in 1811 after John Parkinson of [[Old Bolingbroke]] made several attempts to find [[coal]].<ref name=hist>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:Xcf5GGuKZjwJ:www.e-lindsey.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/3C7DD823-9CC3-48F0-9194-66C3EFE9C1F7/0/woodhall_spa_conservation_area_appraisal_draft.pdf+woodhall+spa+well+collapsed&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjU-7m8sFcm55NM6F9EBXE41ErZPP8hQfATJ-m7TfEjdjQ9Bt3axe-mYkT5FOqNlX0aPQpuask3qAejS1qvNovpj8LoQGf8j9GrKYORCtc7UEKKOm6LSaTUUqPVWgCb5hdY5Szn&sig=AHIEtbTc1krGEJuLtHkPys0HjQ6k69L8MA|publisher=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area Appraisal|accessdate=28 May 2011|page=13}}</ref> After spending several thousand pounds and sinking a [[shaft mining|shaft]] over 1,000 feet deep, the enterprise was abandoned on account of the now rising [[spring (hydrosphere)|spring]].<ref name=Kelly-1919>{{cite book |date=1919 |title=Kelly's Directory \u2013 Lincolnshire |url=http://specialcollections.le.ac.uk/digital/collection/p16445coll4/id/167125.pdf |publisher=Kelly's Directories Ltd |location=London |pages=611-614 |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>Hembry, Phyllis; Cowie, Leonard W; Cowie Evelyn E. (1997). [https://books.google.com/books?id=QvDWk4YMAR8C&pg=PA148&dq=parkinson+woodhall+spa+bolingbroke&hl=en&ei=SdrgTb26BZSu8QOn_4n1Bg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=parkinson%20woodhall%20spa%20bolingbroke&f=false ''British spas from 1815 to the present: a social history''] p.148; Farleigh Dickinson University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-8386-3748-7}}. Retrieved 28 May 2011</ref> The spring flows daily through soft spongy [[Rock (geology)|rock]] at a depth of 520 feet.<ref name=Kelly-1919/>\n\nAbout 1834, the then Lord of the Manor, Thomas Hotchkin, ascertained by [[analysis]] that the water was in fact valuable, being an [[iodine]] and [[bromine]] containing [[mineral spring]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Spas Of and Principal Sea Bathing Places|year=1841|publisher=Henry Colburn|pages=110\u2013113|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DKQ8AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA111&dq=hotchkins+woodhall+spa&hl=en&ei=q6LgTYjUMsTDhAeqzO21Bg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&sqi=2&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|first=A. B. |last=Granville|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref>  He spent nearly \u00a330,000 sinking a [[water well|well]], and erecting the Spa Baths and the Victoria Hotel.<ref name=hist/><ref>{{cite journal|title=Iodine -  Woodhall Spa and Gardens|journal=The Lancet|year=1853|volume=1|page=508|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CBlAAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA420-IA2&dq=woodhall+spa&hl=en&ei=cn_eTdW1FcrZsgb4pdS4BQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CE4Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=woodhall%20spa&f=false|accessdate=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Victoria Hotel burned down on [[Easter Day]], 4 April 1920, when an electrical fault in the boiler room spread to the linen room above.<ref>{{cite web|title=Victoria Hotel|url=http://www.woodhallspa.org/heritage_victoriahotel.html|publisher=Woodhall Spa Village Website|accessdate=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Second World War===\n{{multiple image\n | align        = right\n | direction    = vertical\n | header       = Dam Busters Memorial\n | header_align = center\n | width        =\n | image1       = The Dam Busters Memorial. - geograph.org.uk - 1552470.jpg\n | width1       = 180\n | caption1     = Memorial to the members of 617 Squadron who took part in the Dam Busters raid\n | image2       =\n | width2       = 180\n | caption2     = Detail on the memorial\n}}\n\nIn the Second World War Woodhall Spa's two main hotels, The Golf Hotel and The Petwood Hotel, were [[wikt:requisition#Verb|requisitioned]] for the [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] and Pinewoods was used to hide military equipment, especially on its northern perimeter. [[RAF Woodhall Spa]] airfield was built to the south of the village<ref>[[Bruce Barrymore Halpenny|Halpenny, Bruce Barrymore]] (1982) ''Action Stations 2 Military Airfields of Lincolnshire and the East Midlands'', p. 207. Patrick Stephens Ltd, {{ISBN|0-85059-484-7}}</ref> in the parish of [[Tattershall Thorpe]]. It closed for operational purposes in 1964, although it is still owned by the [[Ministry of Defence (UK)|Ministry of Defence]], used mainly for jet engine maintenance and testing and is operated as a satellite unit of nearby [[RAF Coningsby]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Thorpe Camp|url=http://home.clara.net/heureka/lincolnshire/thorpe-camp.htm|accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=Pastscape>{{PastScape|mname=RAF Woodhall Spa, Tattershall Thorpe|mnumber=1432038|accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nA memorial wall depicting the breaching of the German dams in [[Operation Chastise]], otherwise known as the \"Dam Busters\" raid, stands in the Royal Gardens (the site of the Royal Hydro Hotel) in the centre of the village. It is dedicated to the memory of those from [[No. 617 Squadron RAF|617 Squadron]] who were killed during the war.<ref>http://www.iwm.org.uk/memorials/item/memorial/20485</ref> The memorial is the location of a local school choir photograph, published in ''Lincolnshire Life'' magazine, which included a black [[Labrador Retriever|Labrador]] dog; the photo-caption asks if this \"mysterious\" animal was [[Nigger (dog)|Guy Gibson's dog]], which was run over and killed shortly before Gibson departed to bomb German dams.<ref name=lincolnshirelife>Halpenny, Bruce Barrymore, [http://www.lincolnshirelife.co.uk/uploads/files/aspects_of_lincolnshire/aspectsoflincolnshire-0509-4.pdf \"The ghost dog of RAF Scampton\"], [http://www.lincolnshirelife.co.uk/index.php?page=aspects-of-lincolnshire ''Lincolnshire Life''] (incomplete), May 2009. Retrieved 13 August 2010.</ref>\n\nMost of the Royal Hydro Hotel and Winter Gardens was destroyed by a German [[parachute mine]] which fell on 17 August 1943, although part of it did survive and became the Mall Hotel.<ref name=\"Horn\"/><ref name=\"Woodhall Spa\"/>  Two civilians were killed.<ref>{{CWGC cemetery|id=4004300|name=Woodhall Spa Urban District|access-date=2 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Post-war===\n\nThe Spa Baths finally closed when the well collapsed in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:Xcf5GGuKZjwJ:www.e-lindsey.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/3C7DD823-9CC3-48F0-9194-66C3EFE9C1F7/0/woodhall_spa_conservation_area_appraisal_draft.pdf+woodhall+spa+well+collapsed&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjU-7m8sFcm55NM6F9EBXE41ErZPP8hQfATJ-m7TfEjdjQ9Bt3axe-mYkT5FOqNlX0aPQpuask3qAejS1qvNovpj8LoQGf8j9GrKYORCtc7UEKKOm6LSaTUUqPVWgCb5hdY5Szn&sig=AHIEtbTc1krGEJuLtHkPys0HjQ6k69L8MA|publisher=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area Appraisal|accessdate=27 May 2011|page=15}}</ref> They currently stand in a dilapidated condition.\n\n==Historic estates==\n\n====Woodhall Spa Manor====\n\nThe building and grounds of Woodhall Spa Manor are intrinsically linked to the development of the village from its formative years. The earliest references to this site show that a small hunting lodge was present here in the late 18th century. The inner library room still retains original Jacobean carving over the fireplace and is believed to be the earliest remaining feature from the hunting lodge days.\n\nWoodhall Lodge or Wood Corner, as it was then known, became the property of one Thomas Hotchkin of Rutland, Lord of the Manor of Thimbleby and Woodhall. Hotchkin had inherited many manors throughout Rutland and Lincolnshire but Woodhall Lodge was his particular favourite and where he spent most of his time. Half a mile to the west of the grounds, close to the present Kinema, Thomas Hotchkin had built a spa bath in the late 1830s, having by chance discovered the healing properties of the iodine-rich water in a disused mine shaft on his land. In 1842 White's Directory describes Woodhall Spa as \"a modern watering place \u2026 with just over 300 souls\" and Thomas Hotchkin as living in Woodhall Lodge, \"a neat mansion near the spa'.\n\nAfter his passing, four further generations of the Hotchkin Family lived in Woodhall Lodge. At some point during the last century, it was renamed as the Old Manor or Manor House. During the residence of Thomas Hotchkin's great grandson, [[Stafford Hotchkin|Stafford Vere Hotchkin]] (1876\u20131953), who helped to redesign the adjacent world-rated golf course which bears his name, there were major additions to the building. Around 1905 the south-west corner and east wings were built, greatly enlarging the footprint of the property, leaving the front entrance wholly Georgian, whilst, to the left and right are the Edwardian additions. The magnificent sweeping staircase, the beautiful hallway and Queens Room fireplaces, and the mahogany panelled entrance to the library all date from this period of high elegance. In 1965, Thomas Hotchkin\u2019s great great grandson, Neil Stafford Hotchkin (1914\u20132004), sold the property to the National Farmers Union and it was converted into offices as the company\u2019s regional headquarters.  Around twenty five years later, it was sold to a local businessman, who continued to run it as offices for various Lincolnshire companies. In 2013 new owners renamed it Woodhall Spa Manor and it now serves as a wedding and event venue.\n\n====The Tower-on-the-Moor====\n[[File:WSGC Tower by 3rd.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Tower as seen from [[Woodhall Spa Golf Club]]]]\nThe Tower-on-the-Moor, an octagonal, four-storey, red brick-built tower, is the stair turret of what is believed to have been a hunting lodge, built in the mid&ndash;15th century for [[Ralph de Cromwell, 3rd Baron Cromwell]] whose fortified house, [[Tattershall Castle (Lincolnshire)|Tattershall Castle]], was located {{convert|4|mi|km|0}} to the south.<ref name=BLB>{{cite web|title=British Listed Buildings|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-195247-the-tower-on-the-moor-woodhall-spa|publisher=British Listed Buildings|accessdate=28 April 2011}}</ref> It is a Grade II* [[Listed Building]]<ref name=BLB/> and a scheduled [[Ancient Monument]].<ref>{{NHLE|num=1017216|desc=Tower on the Moor|accessdate=26 June 2017}}</ref>  Documentary sources indicate that the tower was partly dismantled in 1472, when bricks from the Tower on the Moor were used for repairs at Tattershall Castle.<ref>(Scheduling Report)</ref><ref>Simpson, W.D. (ed), 1960, _The building accounts of Tattershall Castle, 1434-1472_ (Lincoln Record Society 55) p. 39, 78 and note</ref> One of the older roads in Woodhall Spa, ''Tor-O-Moor Road'' is named after the tower.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\nThe Tower is adjacent to the 3rd green of the Hotchkin Course at [[Woodhall Spa Golf Club]]. It is a notable feature of the course and has been adopted as the emblem of the golf club.\n\n==Geography==\nWoodhall Spa lies at the southwestern edge of the Central Lincolnshire Vale, between the Rivers [[River Witham|Witham]] and [[River Bain|Bain]]. The village is largely flat rising gently towards the east, and is surrounded towards the north and east by a mixture of ancient and planted woodland. To the south west can be found many sand and gravel excavation pits, some still in use and some abandoned, many of which are now protected nature reserves. Much of the land on which the village is built was once extensive [[heathland]] with a light [[fluvial]] sandy soil.<ref>{{cite web|title=Central Lincolnshire Vale|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:RJ7X4imxWT8J:www.naturalengland.org.uk/Images/jca44_tcm6-4932.pdf+woodhall+spa+soil&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESiXQrL5ZtSlooIMFSxzjh9uCQEYtwe0ALsLnZmQSJvcolURfzWGO3FjF6jNDu7y-KrapxavBy1UwgU_WyH1PkfruUFkjNtT0K2WiUYGSn3I0BmeSp0Mkgbn8Am16JxvMEOrXFMN&sig=AHIEtbSvPb3pcxraCfKpp4tUlpUQkTY8Aw|publisher=Natural England|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref> Well-preserved areas of heathland can be seen at Moor Farm Nature Reserve on Wellsyke Lane, where plants include [[tormentil]], [[bell heather]] and [[climbing corydalis]].\n\nThe abundance of [[sand]] and [[gravel]] in the soil around Woodhall Spa explains the formation of acidic heathland, in a county otherwise characterised by calcareous bedrock and naturally [[alkaline]] soils. Lincolnshire's heathland has historically been eroded by agriculture, forestry, quarrying and peat-cutting and is threatened by falling water-tables<ref>[https://www.nelincs.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/201110-LincolnshireBAP-3rd-edition.pdf Lincolnshire Biodiversity Partnership - Lincolnshire Biodiversity Action PlaN]</ref> To the northwest, south and immediately west can be found arable farmland, with the River Witham lying one mile to the west of the village centre and arable fenland beyond that.\n\nThe [[civil parish]] of Woodhall Spa borders the civil parishes of [[Tattershall Thorpe]], [[Timberland, Lincolnshire|Timberland]], [[Martin, Lincolnshire|Martin]], Stixwould and Woodhall, [[Roughton, Lincolnshire|Roughton]], and [[Kirkby on Bain]].\n\n{{Geographic location\n|title = '''Destinations from Woodhall Spa'''\n|Northwest = [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]], [[Gainsborough, Lincolnshire|Gainsborough]], [[Bardney]]\n|North     = [[Grimsby]], [[Market Rasen]], [[Wragby]], [[Stixwould]],\n|Northeast = [[Mablethorpe]], [[Louth, Lincolnshire|Louth]], [[Horncastle, Lincolnshire|Horncastle]], [[Woodhall, Lincolnshire|Old Woodhall]]\n|West      = [[Metheringham]], [[Newark-on-Trent]], Martin Dales, [[Martin, Lincolnshire|Martin]]\n|Centre    = Woodhall Spa\n|East      = [[Kirkby on Bain]], [[Skegness]], [[Spilsby]], [[Burgh Le Marsh]],\n|Southwest = [[Billinghay]], [[Sleaford]], [[Grantham]]\n|South     = [[Tattershall]], [[Coningsby]], [[Heckington]], [[Swineshead, Lincolnshire|Swineshead]], [[Spalding, Lincolnshire|Spalding]],\n|Southeast = [[Tumby Moorside|Tumby]], [[Mareham le Fen]], [[Stickney, Lincolnshire|Stickney]], [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]],\n}}\n\n<!-- population table -->\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; width:70%; border:0; text-align:center; line-height:120%;\"\n! colspan=\"12\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"|Population of Woodhall Spa [[Civil Parish]]\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#9cc; color:navy; height:17px;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1901\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1911\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1921\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1931\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1951\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1961\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 2001\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 2011\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!  style=\"background:#9cc; color:navy; height:17px;\"| Population<ref>{{cite web|title=Vision of Britain|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_page.jsp?data_theme=T_POP&data_cube=N_TOT_POP&u_id=10464109&c_id=10001043&add=N|work=Woodhall Spa Population|publisher=University of Portsmouth|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 988\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1,484\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1,635\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1,372\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1,671\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1,978\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 3,657\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 4,003\n|}\n\n==Governance==\nAn [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]] of the same name exists. This ward includes [[Kirkby on Bain]] with a total population taken at the 2011 Census of 4,298.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/woodhall-spa-e05005605#sthash.IvWKFoyQ.dpbs|title=Ward population 2011|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe more ancient parish of Kirkstead was amalgamated with Woodhall Spa in the early 1980s, thus formalising what was already a reality.<ref>{{cite web|title=GENUKI|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LIN/Kirkstead/|work=Kirkstead|publisher=GENUKI|accessdate=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Railways==\n{{main|Woodhall Spa railway station}}\nIn 1846 the [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway company]] purchased the land to build a {{convert|58|mi|km}} rail link from [[Peterborough]] to [[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]]. Work commenced in 1847 and the line opened on 17 October 1848.<ref name=Dis/> Kirkstead Station, later renamed [[Woodhall Junction railway station|Woodhall Junction]], was one of seven between Lincoln and Boston. A branch line to [[Horncastle, Lincolnshire|Horncastle]], which included [[Woodhall Spa railway station]], was opened on 11 August 1855.<ref name=Dis/>\n\nThe railways brought increasing popularity, and an elegant [[spa town]] with hotels and guest houses on wide tree-lined avenues, largely designed by Richard Adolphus Came, grew up around the original facilities. He stated in his designs that none of the roads shall be \"streets\", which is still true today, and the roads built since have also been lined with various trees.<ref name=CA/> In 1886 the estate was purchased by a [[syndicate]], and extensive alterations and improvements were made.<ref name=Kelly-1919/> The Victoria Hotel and the Spa Baths were greatly modified by the syndicate,<ref name=CA>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Conservation area|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:Xcf5GGuKZjwJ:www.e-lindsey.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/3C7DD823-9CC3-48F0-9194-66C3EFE9C1F7/0/woodhall_spa_conservation_area_appraisal_draft.pdf+woodhall+spa+well+collapsed&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjU-7m8sFcm55NM6F9EBXE41ErZPP8hQfATJ-m7TfEjdjQ9Bt3axe-mYkT5FOqNlX0aPQpuask3qAejS1qvNovpj8LoQGf8j9GrKYORCtc7UEKKOm6LSaTUUqPVWgCb5hdY5Szn&sig=AHIEtbTc1krGEJuLtHkPys0HjQ6k69L8MA|publisher=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area Appraisal|accessdate=27 May 2011|page=14}}</ref> a group of investors including [[Richard Webster, 1st Viscount Alverstone|Lord Alverstone]], Lord Iddesleigh and [[Edward Stanhope]] MP in 1887.<ref name=CA/>\n\nWoodhall and Woodhall Spa stations closed along with the rest of the Boston to Lincoln line in 1971 and demolition came soon afterwards.<ref name=Dis>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Station|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/w/woodhall_spa/index.shtml|publisher=Disused Stations|accessdate=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Recreation and facilities==\n\n===The Kinema in the Woods===\n{{main|The Kinema in the Woods}}\nThe Kinema in the Woods is located at the centre of the Pinewoods, next to the now derelict Spa Baths and opposite the site of the former Victoria Hotel. Housed in a converted cricket pavilion, it opened in 1922 as one of the first cinemas in Britain. It is the last cinema in the country to employ back [[Movie projector|projection]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Tourism and Leisure: The Kinema in the Woods|url=http://www.woodhallspa.org/wp/?page_id=25|website=woodhallspa.org|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> and also offers regular entertainment on an original [[John Compton (organ builder)#Compton organs|Compton Kinestra 3 Manual / 9 Rank organ]]. The organ was installed in 1987; its console (which is the only surviving Japanese Lacquered console in the UK) was originally installed in the Super Cinema, Charing Cross Road, London between 1927 and 1943.\n<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perman|first1=Chris|title=Kinema in the Woods & Kinema Too| url=http://cinematreasures.org/theaters/6373| website= cinematreasures.org| accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Jubilee Park===\nJubilee Park, opened in 1937, lies adjacent to the Pinewoods and includes [[Jubilee Park Swimming Pool]], a heated [[lido|outdoor swimming pool]]. The park also offers [[tennis courts]], a [[bowling green]], children's playground, croquet and a [[cricket ground]],<ref name=Horn/> which is home to Woodhall Spa Cricket Club.<ref name=Crick>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Cricket Club|url=http://woodhallspa.play-cricket.com/home/aboutUs.asp|publisher=England & Wales Cricket Board|accessdate=27 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130131221136/http://woodhallspa.play-cricket.com/home/aboutUs.asp|archivedate=31 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 22 December 2010, [[BBC Radio 4]] broadcast the half-hour-long ''Australian Wanted in Woodhall Spa'', presented by Chris Ledgard and detailing overseas players playing for English amateur cricket clubs.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00wsqv9 Radio 4]</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, East Lindsey Council sold Jubilee Park to the Woodhall Spa residents for \u00a31.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jubilee Park Sold|url=http://www.horncastlenews.co.uk/news/business/local-businesses/jubilee_park_sold_to_woodhall_spa_residents_for_1_1_2200689|accessdate=25 May 2011|newspaper=Horncastle News|date=22 December 2010}}</ref> It is currently undergoing renovations.<ref>{{cite news|title=This Is Lincolnshire|url=http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/news/won-t-let-winter-ruin-good-summer/article-3510934-detail/article.html|accessdate=25 May 2011|newspaper=Lincolnshire Echo|date=3 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110506042319/http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/news/won-t-let-winter-ruin-good-summer/article-3510934-detail/article.html|archive-date=6 May 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Jubilee Park is next to a caravan park of the same name.\n\n===Woodlands===\n[[File:Pine Woods Woodhall Spa - geograph.org.uk - 102320.jpg|thumbnail|The Pinewoods]]\nThe Pinewoods is a {{convert|19|acre|ha}} [[woodland]] at the centre of the village, owned by the [[Woodland Trust]].<ref name=Pine>{{cite web|title=The Pinewoods|url=http://www.woodlandtrust.org.uk/en/our-woods/Pages/about-this-wood.aspx?wood=4160|publisher=Woodland Trust|accessdate=24 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329064244/http://www.woodlandtrust.org.uk/en/our-woods/Pages/about-this-wood.aspx?wood=4160|archivedate=29 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is made up of mature oak, Scots pine, beech and birch. Originally scrub land, later becoming part of the grounds of the Victoria Hotel, it attracts visitors, particularly in the spring and autumn.<ref name=Pine/>\n\n[[Ostler's Plantation]] is a Forestry Commission working woodland along the south side of Kirkby Lane to the east of Woodhall Spa. It is open to the public for a range of recreational activities throughout the year. It is primarily pine with oak, birch and some other species around the fringes. It is bordered to the east by [[Kirkby Moor Nature Reserve]] and to the south by the former RAF Woodhall Spa, which has recently been purchased by the [[Lincolnshire Wildlife Trust]] soon to become a nature reserve.\n\nTo the east of the village between Horncastle Road and Kirkby Lane lie Kirkby and Roughton Moors. Once open heathland, these are now almost all wooded, with parts owned by the [[Lincolnshire Wildlife Trust]] and managed as two nature reserves: [[Kirkby Moor Nature Reserve]] and [[Roughton Moor Wood Nature Reserve]]. Both are open to the public and can be accessed from either Kirkby Lane, Wellsyke Lane or Horncastle Road.\n\nThere are more areas of woodland towards [[Horncastle, Lincolnshire|Horncastle]] to the north of the Viking Way/Spa Trail: Highhall Wood is private but with a permissive access footpath through it; White Hall Wood is open to the public and Thornton Wood is private.\n\n===The National Golf Centre===\n{{main|Woodhall Spa Golf Club}}\nThe first nine-hole golf course was opened in Woodhall Spa in 1890, but only survived until 1895 when the land was required for building.<ref name=CA/> A new site was found and another nine-hole [[golf course]] was laid out, but by 1902 it became clear that the golf course would have to find another new home as the land was again required for the expansion of the spa town.<ref name=CA/>\n\nLocal landowner Stafford Vere Hotchkin, offered a sandy tract of land off the Horncastle Road to build an 18-hole course. The course was designed by [[Harry Vardon]] and was formally opened for play on 24 April 1905. It was remodelled in 1911 by Harry Colt, and again by Hotchkin himself in the 1920s.<ref name=Golf>{{cite web|title=Golf Club|url=http://www.woodhallspa.org/club_woodhallgolf.html|publisher=Woodhall Spa Website|accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nWomersley House was built by the Hotchkin family, which was instrumental in the development of the adjoining Hotchkin Golf Course\u2014now the headquarters of the [[English Golf Union]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 5: Properties worth more than \u00a31 million for sale in Lincolnshire|url=http://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/5-properties-worth-1-million-sale-lincolnshire/story-19854910-detail/story.html|website=lincolnshirelive.co.uk|publisher=Lincolnshire Echo|accessdate=11 December 2016}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> who bought the course in 1995 to set up a [[National Golf Centre]].<ref name=Golf/><ref name=CNGU>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Golf Club|url=http://www.woodhallspagolf.com/?splash=1|publisher=2011 Council of National Golf Unions|accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref> A second course, \"The Bracken\", opened for play in 1998 alongside the original course, now named \"the Hotchkin\".<ref name=CNGU/> The [[St Andrews Trophy]] was held at the golf course in 1996.<!--{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}No citation needed; it's on the wikipage to which it's linked.-->\n\nMost recently, it was voted 20th best course in the world by ''[[Today's Golfer]]'' magazine in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa |url=http://admin.todaysgolfer.co.uk/Golf/courses/Top-100-Golf-Courses-in-the-World/The-Worlds-Top-100-20---11/Woodhall-Spa-Golf-Club/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120701102850/http://admin.todaysgolfer.co.uk/Golf/courses/Top-100-Golf-Courses-in-the-World/The-Worlds-Top-100-20---11/Woodhall-Spa-Golf-Club/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=1 July 2012 |publisher=Today's Golfer Magazine |accessdate=27 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Footpaths and Walking===\nThe [[Viking Way]] is a {{convert|147|mi|km}} [[long-distance footpath]] which passes through Woodhall Spa en route between the [[Humber Bridge]] and [[Oakham]] in [[Rutland]].<ref name=Vik>{{cite web|title=Viking Way|url=http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_id=504|publisher=Long Distance Walkers Association|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Spa Trail - geograph.org.uk - 1198159.jpg|thumb|180px|right|Spa Trail]]\nThe Spa Trail runs for {{convert|3.3|mi|km}} along the [[Viking Way]] and the old [[Horncastle Railway]] between Sandy Lane near Woodhall Spa and Thornton Lodge near Horncastle.<ref name=Vik/><ref>{{cite web|title=Visit Lincolnshire|url=http://www.visitlincolnshire.com/site/things-to-do/activities/the-spa-trail-p341081|work=The Spa Trail|publisher=Lincolnshire County Council|accessdate=26 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725215457/http://www.visitlincolnshire.com/site/things-to-do/activities/the-spa-trail-p341081|archivedate=25 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> With the Viking Way it forms a continuous traffic-free footpath between Woodhall Spa and [[Horncastle, Lincolnshire|Horncastle]].\n\nThe Water Rail Way is a {{Convert|25|mi|km}} long part of the [[National Cycle Network]] that runs from [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]] to [[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]], following as closely as possible the banks of the [[River Witham]]. Between Woodhall Spa and Lincoln it consists of a tarmacked path that runs along the route of the former railway line from Boston to Lincoln. It was built and financed by [[Sustrans]] organisation, and was finally completed and opened in November 2008. It is open to all forms of non-motorised transport, forming part of [[National Cycle Network|NCN]] Route 1. Named primarily after its route and former use, the path is also named after a native but seldom-seen wading bird called the [[water rail]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Water Rail Way|url=http://www.sustrans.org.uk/sustrans-near-you/midlands/easy-rides-in-the-midlands/water-rail-way|publisher=Sustrans|accessdate=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nThe Legacy Woodhall Spa Hotel opened in 1882 as the Eagle Lodge Hotel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lincs To The Past|url=http://www.lincstothepast.com/Woodhall-Spa-Hotel-including-The-Lodge-pub--Woodhall-Spa/246360.record?pt=S|work=Woodhall Spa Hotel|publisher=Lincolnshire Archives|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref>  It was converted into a nursing home in the 1960s and reopened as a hotel in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|title=Legacy Woodhall Spa Hotel|url=http://www.legacy-hotels.co.uk/legacy-woodhall/index.php|publisher=Legacy Woodhall Spa Hotel|accessdate=27 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511213506/http://www.legacy-hotels.co.uk/legacy-woodhall/index.php|archivedate=11 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nThe Golf Hotel was originally called Clevedon House and has been a school, a club and a hotel of the same name.<ref>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:Xcf5GGuKZjwJ:www.e-lindsey.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/3C7DD823-9CC3-48F0-9194-66C3EFE9C1F7/0/woodhall_spa_conservation_area_appraisal_draft.pdf+woodhall+spa+well+collapsed&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjU-7m8sFcm55NM6F9EBXE41ErZPP8hQfATJ-m7TfEjdjQ9Bt3axe-mYkT5FOqNlX0aPQpuask3qAejS1qvNovpj8LoQGf8j9GrKYORCtc7UEKKOm6LSaTUUqPVWgCb5hdY5Szn&sig=AHIEtbTc1krGEJuLtHkPys0HjQ6k69L8MA|page= 40|publisher=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area Appraisal|accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref><ref name=Horn/>\n\nThe Royal Hydro Hotel and the attached Winter Gardens were mostly destroyed in a German air raid during [[World War II]] in August 1943, although part survived and became the Mall Hotel.<ref name=Horn>{{cite web|title=Horncastle Lincolnshire|url=http://www.horncastleuk.com/historydetail.php?id=735&cid=592&f=Horncastle|publisher=Visitor UK|accessdate=27 May 2011}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"Woodhall Spa\">{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa|url=http://www.visitlincolnshire.com/aviation/towns-and-villages/woodhall-spa-p148871|publisher=Lincolnshire County Council|accessdate=26 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725215515/http://www.visitlincolnshire.com/aviation/towns-and-villages/woodhall-spa-p148871|archivedate=25 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Petwood Hotel is so called because it was originally built at the turn of the 20th century as a house for Grace, Lady Weigall, who had it constructed in her favourite wood, her \"pet wood\". Lady Weigall turned her former home into a hotel in 1933.<ref name=Horn/>\n\nThe heyday of Woodhall Spa was recorded by a local photographer, John Wield, and many of his photographs are displayed in the [[Woodhall Spa Cottage Museum]], which was his home.<ref name=Horn/><ref>{{cite web|title=Visit Lincolnshire|url=http://www.visitlincolnshire.com/site/things-to-do/woodhall-spa-cottage-museum-p15831|work=Woodhall Spa Cottage Museum|publisher=Lincolnshire County Council|accessdate=26 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717224312/http://www.visitlincolnshire.com/site/things-to-do/woodhall-spa-cottage-museum-p15831|archivedate=17 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Churches==\n[[Saint Peter]]'s church was built in 1893,<ref name=Peter>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Heritage| url=http://www.woodhallspa.org/heritage_stpeters_church.html|publisher=Woodhall Spa Heritage|accessdate=28 April 2011}}</ref> although it was not until 1915 that it was legally designated the [[parish church]].<ref name=\"Peter\"/> The building was designed by architect [[C. Hodgson Fowler|C H Fowler]] in brick with a half-timbered bell turret, and with glass by [[James Powell and Sons|Powell's]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Pevsner, Nikolaus|author2=Harris, John|editor1-last=Antram|editor1-first=Nicholas|title=The Buildings of England: Lincolnshire|date=1989|publisher=Penguin|location=London|isbn=0 14 071027 2|page=810|edition=2nd}}</ref> Until then the little church of [[Saint Andrew]], built in 1846,<ref name=Cox>Cox, J. Charles (1916); ''Lincolnshire'' p. 343; ''Methuen & Co. Ltd.''; Retrieved 28 April 2011</ref> was the parish church, but was too small for the rapidly growing town.<ref name=\"Peter\"/>\nWoodhall Spa is now part of a group of six [[Anglican]] parishes comprising:\nWoodhall Spa and Kirkstead, [[Stixwould]], [[Horsington, Lincolnshire|Horsington]], Langton with [[Woodhall, Lincolnshire|Old Woodhall]], and [[Bucknall, Lincolnshire|Bucknall]] with [[Tupholme]].<ref name=Church>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Heritage| url=http://www.woodhallspa.org/services_worship.html|publisher=Woodhall Spa Heritage|accessdate=28 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Church of [[Blessed Virgin Mary (Roman Catholic)|Our Lady]] and [[Saint Peter]],<ref name=\"Church\"/> built in 1893,<ref name=Cox/> is Woodhall Spa's [[Roman Catholic]] church.\n\n==Education==\n\nThere are two schools within Woodhall Spa; [[St Hugh's School, Woodhall Spa|St Hugh's School]],<ref>[http://www.st-hughs.lincs.sch.uk St Hugh's]</ref> a preparatory boarding school on Cromwell Avenue, and St Andrew's C of E Primary School on King Edward Crescent.\n\nSecondary schools are outside Woodhall and include [[Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School, Horncastle|Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School]] and [[Banovallum School]] in [[Horncastle, Lincolnshire|Horncastle]], and [[Gartree Community School]] in [[Tattershall]].\n\n==Twin Town==\n\n* {{flagicon|France}} [[Ro\u00e9z\u00e9-sur-Sarthe]] in [[Pays de la Loire]] which is {{circa}}{{Convert|6|mi|km}} south west of [[Le Mans]]. The charter was signed in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lincolnshire Twinning Federation|url=http://www.twinninglincs.org/Woodhall%20Spa.htm|work=Woodhall Spa|publisher=Lincolnshire Twinning Federation|accessdate=26 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217081331/http://www.twinninglincs.org/Woodhall%20Spa.htm|archivedate=17 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Notable residents ==\n<!-- NOTE - Do not add people who have no independent cited references to Woodhall association within their own Wikipedia article. If no Wikipedia article, they should have independent cited evidence of being Woodhall associated and of being well-known at least nationally, otherwise additions will not meet Wikipedia Notability standards and will be removed. Discuss additions and edits on the talk page, and add them in alphabetical order.-->\n\n* [[Air Vice-Marshal]] Allan Blackley [[CBE]]; commandant of the [[Central Flying School]] at [[RAF Scampton]] 1985&ndash;7{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n<!--* [[Jason Bradbury]]; went to St Andrews C of E Primary School Not according to his WP entry-->\n* [[Violet Dickson]] [[DBE]] (1896&ndash;1991); attended the village's Miss Lunn's High School in the early 1900s{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n* [[Flying Officer]] Ray Grayston (1918&ndash;2010); one of the last survivors of the Dambusters' raid and was flight engineer of the Lancaster that breached the Eder Dam.<ref>{{cite news|title=Flying Officer Ray Grayston|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/military-obituaries/air-force-obituaries/7647326/Flying-Officer-Ray-Grayston.html|accessdate=11 December 2016|date=28 April 2010|work=Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n* Michael Hardie [[OBE]]; [[List of Diplomats of the United Kingdom to the Gambia|High Commissioner to the Gambia]] from 1994-5<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U18989 |title=HARDIE, Michael John |work=Who's Who 2009 |publisher=A & C Black |year=2008 |accessdate=24 July 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Leonard Cheshire]] {{postnominals|country=GBR|sep=,|VC|OM|DSO|DFC}} (1917\u20131992); lived here during his time as Officer Commanding [[No. 617 Squadron RAF|No. 617 Squadron]] (November 1943\u2013July 1944) and was created a [[life peer]] as ''Baron Cheshire, of Woodhall in the County of Lincolnshire''<ref name=\"nyt1992\">\"Lord Cheshire, World War II Hero Who Founded Homes for Sick, 74,\" ''The New York Times.'' 2 August 1992.</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52608 |date=22 July 1991 |page=11147}}</ref> in 1991\n* [[John Hartley (cricketer)|John Hartley]] (1874&ndash;1963); Test cricketer who died in Woodhall Spa\n*[[Monica Irimia]] Cheeky Girl and musician currently resides in Woodhall Spa{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n* [[Ursula Niebuhr]] (1907&ndash;1997); Theologian{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n* [[Steve Plater]] (b.1972); motorcyclist\n* [[David Tarttelin]] (b.1929); painter who, as a child was evacuated to Woodhall Spa during the Second World War\n* [[Adrian Tchaikovsky]]; Author<ref>{{cite web|title=Adrian Tchaikovsky|url=http://www.panmacmillan.com/search?searchtext=Adrian+Tchaikovsky&searchmode=anyword|publisher=Pan Macmillan|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Robert Webb (actor)|Robert Webb]] (b.1972); actor, comedian and writer who grew up in Woodhall Spa.<ref>{{cite news|title=Comedy star goes back to School|url=http://www.horncastlenews.co.uk/news/comedy-star-goes-back-to-school-1-842598|accessdate=11 December 2016|work=Horncastle News|date=14 April 2006}}</ref>\n* Sir [[Archibald Weigall]] {{postnominals|country=GBR|sep=,|KCMG}} Baronet Weigall of Woodhall Spa (1874&ndash;1952); Governor of South Australia<ref name=Horn/>\n* [[David Wigley]] (b.1981); cricketer{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n* [[Willie Hamilton]] (1917&ndash;2000); former Labour MP and noted republican<ref>{{cite news|last1=Roth|first1=Andrew|title=Willie Hamilton Obituary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2000/jan/27/guardianobituaries|accessdate=11 December 2016|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Woodhall Spa- Tower on the Moor (geograph 3089843).jpg|Tower-on-the-Moor\nFile:Spa baths - geograph.org.uk - 1198182.jpg|The derelict Spa Baths in 2009\nFile:The Golf Hotel, Woodhall Spa - geograph.org.uk - 549435.jpg|The Golf Hotel\nFile:The Cottage Museum, Woodhall Spa - geograph.org.uk - 949455.jpg|The Cottage Museum, Woodhall Spa\nFile:Kirkstead Abbey ruin - geograph.org.uk - 694757.jpg|[[Kirkstead Abbey]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of spa towns in the United Kingdom]]\n* [https://archive.is/20130829131252/http://www.lincolnshireinfocus.co.uk/articles/15082013-Woodhall_Spa/ Article on the history of Woodhall Spa]\n* [[Kirkstead]]\n** [[Kirkstead Abbey]]\n** [[St Leonard's Without]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Woodhall Spa}}\n* {{PastScape|mnumber=1432038 |mname=Woodhall Spa Airfield|accessdate=}}\n* [http://lincoln.ourchurchweb.org.uk/woodhallspa/ Woodhall Spa Group of Parishes]\n* [http://www.woodhallspa.org Woodhall Spa Community Website]\n* [http://www.lincolnshirepga.org.uk/woodhall-spa.aspx Lincolnshire PGA - Woodhall Spa Golf Glub]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://www.thekinemainthewoods.co.uk The Kinema In The Woods Official website]\n* [http://www.aquasante.co.uk/home.htm Aqua Sante Spa]\n* [http://www.WoodhallSpaManor.com Woodhall Spa Manor]\n* [http://www.catholicchurchwoodhallspa.org Our Lady and St Peter Catholic Church website]\n* [http://www.st-hughs.lincs.sch.uk St. Hugh's school Website]\n\n{{Portal bar|England|United Kingdom}}\n{{Lincolnshire|state=collapsed}}\n{{East Lindsey (district)|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:East Lindsey District]]\n[[Category:Spa towns in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country                  = England\n|official_name            = Woodhall Spa\n|static_image_name        = Kinema in the Woods.jpg\n|static_image_caption     = Kinema in the Woods\n|coordinates              = {{coord|53.1515|-0.2183|display=inline,title}}\n|os_grid_reference        = TF196631\n| population              = 4,003\n| population_density_km2  =\n| population_ref          = (Including Kirkstead. 2011)<ref>Census, 2011</ref>\n|shire_district           = [[East Lindsey]]\n| shire_county            = [[Lincolnshire]]\n|region                   = East Midlands\n|constituency_westminster = [[Louth and Horncastle (UK Parliament constituency)|Louth and Horncastle]]\n|post_town                = WOODHALL SPA\n|postcode_district        = LN10\n|postcode_area            = LN\n|dial_code                = 01526\n|london_distance_mi       = 115<!-- straight line per MOS \u2013 constant and comparable with other place distances -->\n|london_direction         = S\n|area_total_km2           = 13.42\n}}\n'''Woodhall Spa''' is a former spa town and civil parish in [[Lincolnshire]], England, on the southern edge of the [[Lincolnshire Wolds]], {{convert|6|mi|km|0}} south-west of [[Horncastle, Lincolnshire|Horncastle]], {{convert|23|mi|km}} west of [[Skegness]], {{convert|15|mi|km}} east-south-east of [[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]] and {{convert|17|mi|km|0}} north-west of [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]]. It is noted for its [[mineral springs]], [[The Kinema in the Woods|cinema]] and its [[Second World War]] association with the [[RAF]] [[No. 617 Squadron RAF#Second World War|617 Squadron]]. The cinema has the last remaining rear screen projector in the country.\n\nMuch of the village's [[Victorian era|Victorian]] elegance remains, and since January 1991 much of the centre has been a designated [[conservation area]].<ref name=Cons>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:Xcf5GGuKZjwJ:www.e-lindsey.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/3C7DD823-9CC3-48F0-9194-66C3EFE9C1F7/0/woodhall_spa_conservation_area_appraisal_draft.pdf+woodhall+spa+well+collapsed&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjU-7m8sFcm55NM6F9EBXE41ErZPP8hQfATJ-m7TfEjdjQ9Bt3axe-mYkT5FOqNlX0aPQpuask3qAejS1qvNovpj8LoQGf8j9GrKYORCtc7UEKKOm6LSaTUUqPVWgCb5hdY5Szn&sig=AHIEtbTc1krGEJuLtHkPys0HjQ6k69L8MA|publisher=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area Appraisal|page= 5|accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Ancient history===\nA [[mesolithic]] flint blade and a [[neolithic]] stone axe have been found in Woodhall. From the [[Bronze Age]] there is a dagger and a barrow. A [[medieval]] guildhall has been excavated.<ref>[https://www.digital-documents.co.uk/cgi-bin/web-archi.pl?ARCHIFormNGRLetter=TF&ARCHIFormNGR_x=19&ARCHIFormNGR_y=63&password=freesearch@freesearch.com&TownName=WOODHALL%20SPA&county=Lincolnshire&distance=10000&period=&font_size=&placename=Woodhall%20Spa&info2search4=archi_town_search&keywords= Archi UK]</ref>\n\n===Development===\nWoodhall Spa came about by accident in 1811 after John Parkinson of [[Old Bolingbroke]] made several attempts to find [[coal]].<ref name=hist>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:Xcf5GGuKZjwJ:www.e-lindsey.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/3C7DD823-9CC3-48F0-9194-66C3EFE9C1F7/0/woodhall_spa_conservation_area_appraisal_draft.pdf+woodhall+spa+well+collapsed&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjU-7m8sFcm55NM6F9EBXE41ErZPP8hQfATJ-m7TfEjdjQ9Bt3axe-mYkT5FOqNlX0aPQpuask3qAejS1qvNovpj8LoQGf8j9GrKYORCtc7UEKKOm6LSaTUUqPVWgCb5hdY5Szn&sig=AHIEtbTc1krGEJuLtHkPys0HjQ6k69L8MA|publisher=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area Appraisal|accessdate=28 May 2011|page=13}}</ref> After spending several thousand pounds and sinking a [[shaft mining|shaft]] over 1,000 feet deep, the enterprise was abandoned on account of the now rising [[spring (hydrosphere)|spring]].<ref name=Kelly-1919>{{cite book |date=1919 |title=Kelly's Directory \u2013 Lincolnshire |url=http://specialcollections.le.ac.uk/digital/collection/p16445coll4/id/167125.pdf |publisher=Kelly's Directories Ltd |location=London |pages=611-614 |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>Hembry, Phyllis; Cowie, Leonard W; Cowie Evelyn E. (1997). [https://books.google.com/books?id=QvDWk4YMAR8C&pg=PA148&dq=parkinson+woodhall+spa+bolingbroke&hl=en&ei=SdrgTb26BZSu8QOn_4n1Bg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=parkinson%20woodhall%20spa%20bolingbroke&f=false ''British spas from 1815 to the present: a social history''] p.148; Farleigh Dickinson University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-8386-3748-7}}. Retrieved 28 May 2011</ref> The spring flows daily through soft spongy [[Rock (geology)|rock]] at a depth of 520 feet.<ref name=Kelly-1919/>\n\nAbout 1834, the then Lord of the Manor, Thomas Hotchkin, ascertained by [[analysis]] that the water was in fact valuable, being an [[iodine]] and [[bromine]] containing [[mineral spring]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Spas Of and Principal Sea Bathing Places|year=1841|publisher=Henry Colburn|pages=110\u2013113|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DKQ8AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA111&dq=hotchkins+woodhall+spa&hl=en&ei=q6LgTYjUMsTDhAeqzO21Bg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&sqi=2&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|first=A. B. |last=Granville|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref>  He spent nearly \u00a330,000 sinking a [[water well|well]], and erecting the Spa Baths and the Victoria Hotel.<ref name=hist/><ref>{{cite journal|title=Iodine -  Woodhall Spa and Gardens|journal=The Lancet|year=1853|volume=1|page=508|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CBlAAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA420-IA2&dq=woodhall+spa&hl=en&ei=cn_eTdW1FcrZsgb4pdS4BQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CE4Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=woodhall%20spa&f=false|accessdate=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Victoria Hotel burned down on [[Easter Day]], 4 April 1920, when an electrical fault in the boiler room spread to the linen room above.<ref>{{cite web|title=Victoria Hotel|url=http://www.woodhallspa.org/heritage_victoriahotel.html|publisher=Woodhall Spa Village Website|accessdate=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Second World War===\n{{multiple image\n | align        = right\n | direction    = vertical\n | header       = Dam Busters Memorial\n | header_align = center\n | width        =\n | image1       = The Dam Busters Memorial. - geograph.org.uk - 1552470.jpg\n | width1       = 180\n | caption1     = Memorial to the members of 617 Squadron who took part in the Dam Busters raid\n | image2       =\n | width2       = 180\n | caption2     = Detail on the memorial\n}}\n\nIn the Second World War Woodhall Spa's two main hotels, The Golf Hotel and The Petwood Hotel, were [[wikt:requisition#Verb|requisitioned]] for the [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] and Pinewoods was used to hide military equipment, especially on its northern perimeter. [[RAF Woodhall Spa]] airfield was built to the south of the village<ref>[[Bruce Barrymore Halpenny|Halpenny, Bruce Barrymore]] (1982) ''Action Stations 2 Military Airfields of Lincolnshire and the East Midlands'', p. 207. Patrick Stephens Ltd, {{ISBN|0-85059-484-7}}</ref> in the parish of [[Tattershall Thorpe]]. It closed for operational purposes in 1964, although it is still owned by the [[Ministry of Defence (UK)|Ministry of Defence]], used mainly for jet engine maintenance and testing and is operated as a satellite unit of nearby [[RAF Coningsby]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Thorpe Camp|url=http://home.clara.net/heureka/lincolnshire/thorpe-camp.htm|accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=Pastscape>{{PastScape|mname=RAF Woodhall Spa, Tattershall Thorpe|mnumber=1432038|accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nA memorial wall depicting the breaching of the German dams in [[Operation Chastise]], otherwise known as the \"Dam Busters\" raid, stands in the Royal Gardens (the site of the Royal Hydro Hotel) in the centre of the village. It is dedicated to the memory of those from [[No. 617 Squadron RAF|617 Squadron]] who were killed during the war.<ref>http://www.iwm.org.uk/memorials/item/memorial/20485</ref> The memorial is the location of a local school choir photograph, published in ''Lincolnshire Life'' magazine, which included a black [[Labrador Retriever|Labrador]] dog; the photo-caption asks if this \"mysterious\" animal was [[Nigger (dog)|Guy Gibson's dog]], which was run over and killed shortly before Gibson departed to bomb German dams.<ref name=lincolnshirelife>Halpenny, Bruce Barrymore, [http://www.lincolnshirelife.co.uk/uploads/files/aspects_of_lincolnshire/aspectsoflincolnshire-0509-4.pdf \"The ghost dog of RAF Scampton\"], [http://www.lincolnshirelife.co.uk/index.php?page=aspects-of-lincolnshire ''Lincolnshire Life''] (incomplete), May 2009. Retrieved 13 August 2010.</ref>\n\nMost of the Royal Hydro Hotel and Winter Gardens was destroyed by a German [[parachute mine]] which fell on 17 August 1943, although part of it did survive and became the Mall Hotel.<ref name=\"Horn\"/><ref name=\"Woodhall Spa\"/>  Two civilians were killed.<ref>{{CWGC cemetery|id=4004300|name=Woodhall Spa Urban District|access-date=2 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Post-war===\n\nThe Spa Baths finally closed when the well collapsed in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:Xcf5GGuKZjwJ:www.e-lindsey.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/3C7DD823-9CC3-48F0-9194-66C3EFE9C1F7/0/woodhall_spa_conservation_area_appraisal_draft.pdf+woodhall+spa+well+collapsed&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjU-7m8sFcm55NM6F9EBXE41ErZPP8hQfATJ-m7TfEjdjQ9Bt3axe-mYkT5FOqNlX0aPQpuask3qAejS1qvNovpj8LoQGf8j9GrKYORCtc7UEKKOm6LSaTUUqPVWgCb5hdY5Szn&sig=AHIEtbTc1krGEJuLtHkPys0HjQ6k69L8MA|publisher=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area Appraisal|accessdate=27 May 2011|page=15}}</ref> They currently stand in a dilapidated condition.\n\n==Historic estates==\n\n====Woodhall Spa Manor====\n\nThe building and grounds of Woodhall Spa Manor are intrinsically linked to the development of the village from its formative years. The earliest references to this site show that a small hunting lodge was present here in the late 18th century. The inner library room still retains original Jacobean carving over the fireplace and is believed to be the earliest remaining feature from the hunting lodge days.\n\nWoodhall Lodge or Wood Corner, as it was then known, became the property of one Thomas Hotchkin of Rutland, Lord of the Manor of Thimbleby and Woodhall. Hotchkin had inherited many manors throughout Rutland and Lincolnshire but Woodhall Lodge was his particular favourite and where he spent most of his time. Half a mile to the west of the grounds, close to the present Kinema, Thomas Hotchkin had built a spa bath in the late 1830s, having by chance discovered the healing properties of the iodine-rich water in a disused mine shaft on his land. In 1842 White's Directory describes Woodhall Spa as \"a modern watering place \u2026 with just over 300 souls\" and Thomas Hotchkin as living in Woodhall Lodge, \"a neat mansion near the spa'.\n\nAfter his passing, four further generations of the Hotchkin Family lived in Woodhall Lodge. At some point during the last century, it was renamed as the Old Manor or Manor House. During the residence of Thomas Hotchkin's great grandson, [[Stafford Hotchkin|Stafford Vere Hotchkin]] (1876\u20131953), who helped to redesign the adjacent world-rated golf course which bears his name, there were major additions to the building. Around 1905 the south-west corner and east wings were built, greatly enlarging the footprint of the property, leaving the front entrance wholly Georgian, whilst, to the left and right are the Edwardian additions. The magnificent sweeping staircase, the beautiful hallway and Queens Room fireplaces, and the mahogany panelled entrance to the library all date from this period of high elegance. In 1965, Thomas Hotchkin\u2019s great great grandson, Neil Stafford Hotchkin (1914\u20132004), sold the property to the National Farmers Union and it was converted into offices as the company\u2019s regional headquarters.  Around twenty five years later, it was sold to a local businessman, who continued to run it as offices for various Lincolnshire companies. In 2013 new owners renamed it Woodhall Spa Manor and it now serves as a wedding and event venue.\n\n====The Tower-on-the-Moor====\n[[File:WSGC Tower by 3rd.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Tower as seen from [[Woodhall Spa Golf Club]]]]\nThe Tower-on-the-Moor, an octagonal, four-storey, red brick-built tower, is the stair turret of what is believed to have been a hunting lodge, built in the mid&ndash;15th century for [[Ralph de Cromwell, 3rd Baron Cromwell]] whose fortified house, [[Tattershall Castle (Lincolnshire)|Tattershall Castle]], was located {{convert|4|mi|km|0}} to the south.<ref name=BLB>{{cite web|title=British Listed Buildings|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-195247-the-tower-on-the-moor-woodhall-spa|publisher=British Listed Buildings|accessdate=28 April 2011}}</ref> It is a Grade II* [[Listed Building]]<ref name=BLB/> and a scheduled [[Ancient Monument]].<ref>{{NHLE|num=1017216|desc=Tower on the Moor|accessdate=26 June 2017}}</ref>  Documentary sources indicate that the tower was partly dismantled in 1472, when bricks from the Tower on the Moor were used for repairs at Tattershall Castle.<ref>(Scheduling Report)</ref><ref>Simpson, W.D. (ed), 1960, _The building accounts of Tattershall Castle, 1434-1472_ (Lincoln Record Society 55) p. 39, 78 and note</ref> One of the older roads in Woodhall Spa, ''Tor-O-Moor Road'' is named after the tower.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\nThe Tower is adjacent to the 3rd green of the Hotchkin Course at [[Woodhall Spa Golf Club]]. It is a notable feature of the course and has been adopted as the emblem of the golf club.\n\n==Geography==\nWoodhall Spa lies at the southwestern edge of the Central Lincolnshire Vale, between the Rivers [[River Witham|Witham]] and [[River Bain|Bain]]. The village is largely flat rising gently towards the east, and is surrounded towards the north and east by a mixture of ancient and planted woodland. To the south west can be found many sand and gravel excavation pits, some still in use and some abandoned, many of which are now protected nature reserves. Much of the land on which the village is built was once extensive [[heathland]] with a light [[fluvial]] sandy soil.<ref>{{cite web|title=Central Lincolnshire Vale|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:RJ7X4imxWT8J:www.naturalengland.org.uk/Images/jca44_tcm6-4932.pdf+woodhall+spa+soil&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESiXQrL5ZtSlooIMFSxzjh9uCQEYtwe0ALsLnZmQSJvcolURfzWGO3FjF6jNDu7y-KrapxavBy1UwgU_WyH1PkfruUFkjNtT0K2WiUYGSn3I0BmeSp0Mkgbn8Am16JxvMEOrXFMN&sig=AHIEtbSvPb3pcxraCfKpp4tUlpUQkTY8Aw|publisher=Natural England|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref> Well-preserved areas of heathland can be seen at Moor Farm Nature Reserve on Wellsyke Lane, where plants include [[tormentil]], [[bell heather]] and [[climbing corydalis]].\n\nThe abundance of [[sand]] and [[gravel]] in the soil around Woodhall Spa explains the formation of acidic heathland, in a county otherwise characterised by calcareous bedrock and naturally [[alkaline]] soils. Lincolnshire's heathland has historically been eroded by agriculture, forestry, quarrying and peat-cutting and is threatened by falling water-tables<ref>[https://www.nelincs.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/201110-LincolnshireBAP-3rd-edition.pdf Lincolnshire Biodiversity Partnership - Lincolnshire Biodiversity Action PlaN]</ref> To the northwest, south and immediately west can be found arable farmland, with the River Witham lying one mile to the west of the village centre and arable fenland beyond that.\n\nThe [[civil parish]] of Woodhall Spa borders the civil parishes of [[Tattershall Thorpe]], [[Timberland, Lincolnshire|Timberland]], [[Martin, Lincolnshire|Martin]], Stixwould and Woodhall, [[Roughton, Lincolnshire|Roughton]], and [[Kirkby on Bain]].\n\n{{Geographic location\n|title = '''Destinations from Woodhall Spa'''\n|Northwest = [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]], [[Gainsborough, Lincolnshire|Gainsborough]], [[Bardney]]\n|North     = [[Grimsby]], [[Market Rasen]], [[Wragby]], [[Stixwould]],\n|Northeast = [[Mablethorpe]], [[Louth, Lincolnshire|Louth]], [[Horncastle, Lincolnshire|Horncastle]], [[Woodhall, Lincolnshire|Old Woodhall]]\n|West      = [[Metheringham]], [[Newark-on-Trent]], Martin Dales, [[Martin, Lincolnshire|Martin]]\n|Centre    = Woodhall Spa\n|East      = [[Kirkby on Bain]], [[Skegness]], [[Spilsby]], [[Burgh Le Marsh]],\n|Southwest = [[Billinghay]], [[Sleaford]], [[Grantham]]\n|South     = [[Tattershall]], [[Coningsby]], [[Heckington]], [[Swineshead, Lincolnshire|Swineshead]], [[Spalding, Lincolnshire|Spalding]],\n|Southeast = [[Tumby Moorside|Tumby]], [[Mareham le Fen]], [[Stickney, Lincolnshire|Stickney]], [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]],\n}}\n\n<!-- population table -->\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; width:70%; border:0; text-align:center; line-height:120%;\"\n! colspan=\"12\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"|Population of Woodhall Spa [[Civil Parish]]\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#9cc; color:navy; height:17px;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1901\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1911\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1921\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1931\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1951\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1961\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 2001\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 2011\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!  style=\"background:#9cc; color:navy; height:17px;\"| Population<ref>{{cite web|title=Vision of Britain|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_page.jsp?data_theme=T_POP&data_cube=N_TOT_POP&u_id=10464109&c_id=10001043&add=N|work=Woodhall Spa Population|publisher=University of Portsmouth|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 988\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1,484\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1,635\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1,372\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1,671\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1,978\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 3,657\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 4,003\n|}\n\n==Governance==\nAn [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]] of the same name exists. This ward includes [[Kirkby on Bain]] with a total population taken at the 2011 Census of 4,298.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/woodhall-spa-e05005605#sthash.IvWKFoyQ.dpbs|title=Ward population 2011|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe more ancient parish of Kirkstead was amalgamated with Woodhall Spa in the early 1980s, thus formalising what was already a reality.<ref>{{cite web|title=GENUKI|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LIN/Kirkstead/|work=Kirkstead|publisher=GENUKI|accessdate=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Railways==\n{{main|Woodhall Spa railway station}}\nIn 1846 the [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway company]] purchased the land to build a {{convert|58|mi|km}} rail link from [[Peterborough]] to [[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]]. Work commenced in 1847 and the line opened on 17 October 1848.<ref name=Dis/> Kirkstead Station, later renamed [[Woodhall Junction railway station|Woodhall Junction]], was one of seven between Lincoln and Boston. A branch line to [[Horncastle, Lincolnshire|Horncastle]], which included [[Woodhall Spa railway station]], was opened on 11 August 1855.<ref name=Dis/>\n\nThe railways brought increasing popularity, and an elegant [[spa town]] with hotels and guest houses on wide tree-lined avenues, largely designed by Richard Adolphus Came, grew up around the original facilities. He stated in his designs that none of the roads shall be \"streets\", which is still true today, and the roads built since have also been lined with various trees.<ref name=CA/> In 1886 the estate was purchased by a [[syndicate]], and extensive alterations and improvements were made.<ref name=\"Kellys\"/> The Victoria Hotel and the Spa Baths were greatly modified by the syndicate,<ref name=CA>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Conservation area|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:Xcf5GGuKZjwJ:www.e-lindsey.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/3C7DD823-9CC3-48F0-9194-66C3EFE9C1F7/0/woodhall_spa_conservation_area_appraisal_draft.pdf+woodhall+spa+well+collapsed&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjU-7m8sFcm55NM6F9EBXE41ErZPP8hQfATJ-m7TfEjdjQ9Bt3axe-mYkT5FOqNlX0aPQpuask3qAejS1qvNovpj8LoQGf8j9GrKYORCtc7UEKKOm6LSaTUUqPVWgCb5hdY5Szn&sig=AHIEtbTc1krGEJuLtHkPys0HjQ6k69L8MA|publisher=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area Appraisal|accessdate=27 May 2011|page=14}}</ref> a group of investors including [[Richard Webster, 1st Viscount Alverstone|Lord Alverstone]], Lord Iddesleigh and [[Edward Stanhope]] MP in 1887.<ref name=CA/>\n\nWoodhall and Woodhall Spa stations closed along with the rest of the Boston to Lincoln line in 1971 and demolition came soon afterwards.<ref name=Dis>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Station|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/w/woodhall_spa/index.shtml|publisher=Disused Stations|accessdate=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Recreation and facilities==\n\n===The Kinema in the Woods===\n{{main|The Kinema in the Woods}}\nThe Kinema in the Woods is located at the centre of the Pinewoods, next to the now derelict Spa Baths and opposite the site of the former Victoria Hotel. Housed in a converted cricket pavilion, it opened in 1922 as one of the first cinemas in Britain. It is the last cinema in the country to employ back [[Movie projector|projection]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Tourism and Leisure: The Kinema in the Woods|url=http://www.woodhallspa.org/wp/?page_id=25|website=woodhallspa.org|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> and also offers regular entertainment on an original [[John Compton (organ builder)#Compton organs|Compton Kinestra 3 Manual / 9 Rank organ]]. The organ was installed in 1987; its console (which is the only surviving Japanese Lacquered console in the UK) was originally installed in the Super Cinema, Charing Cross Road, London between 1927 and 1943.\n<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perman|first1=Chris|title=Kinema in the Woods & Kinema Too| url=http://cinematreasures.org/theaters/6373| website= cinematreasures.org| accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Jubilee Park===\nJubilee Park, opened in 1937, lies adjacent to the Pinewoods and includes [[Jubilee Park Swimming Pool]], a heated [[lido|outdoor swimming pool]]. The park also offers [[tennis courts]], a [[bowling green]], children's playground, croquet and a [[cricket ground]],<ref name=Horn/> which is home to Woodhall Spa Cricket Club.<ref name=Crick>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Cricket Club|url=http://woodhallspa.play-cricket.com/home/aboutUs.asp|publisher=England & Wales Cricket Board|accessdate=27 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130131221136/http://woodhallspa.play-cricket.com/home/aboutUs.asp|archivedate=31 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 22 December 2010, [[BBC Radio 4]] broadcast the half-hour-long ''Australian Wanted in Woodhall Spa'', presented by Chris Ledgard and detailing overseas players playing for English amateur cricket clubs.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00wsqv9 Radio 4]</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, East Lindsey Council sold Jubilee Park to the Woodhall Spa residents for \u00a31.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jubilee Park Sold|url=http://www.horncastlenews.co.uk/news/business/local-businesses/jubilee_park_sold_to_woodhall_spa_residents_for_1_1_2200689|accessdate=25 May 2011|newspaper=Horncastle News|date=22 December 2010}}</ref> It is currently undergoing renovations.<ref>{{cite news|title=This Is Lincolnshire|url=http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/news/won-t-let-winter-ruin-good-summer/article-3510934-detail/article.html|accessdate=25 May 2011|newspaper=Lincolnshire Echo|date=3 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110506042319/http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/news/won-t-let-winter-ruin-good-summer/article-3510934-detail/article.html|archive-date=6 May 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Jubilee Park is next to a caravan park of the same name.\n\n===Woodlands===\n[[File:Pine Woods Woodhall Spa - geograph.org.uk - 102320.jpg|thumbnail|The Pinewoods]]\nThe Pinewoods is a {{convert|19|acre|ha}} [[woodland]] at the centre of the village, owned by the [[Woodland Trust]].<ref name=Pine>{{cite web|title=The Pinewoods|url=http://www.woodlandtrust.org.uk/en/our-woods/Pages/about-this-wood.aspx?wood=4160|publisher=Woodland Trust|accessdate=24 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329064244/http://www.woodlandtrust.org.uk/en/our-woods/Pages/about-this-wood.aspx?wood=4160|archivedate=29 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is made up of mature oak, Scots pine, beech and birch. Originally scrub land, later becoming part of the grounds of the Victoria Hotel, it attracts visitors, particularly in the spring and autumn.<ref name=Pine/>\n\n[[Ostler's Plantation]] is a Forestry Commission working woodland along the south side of Kirkby Lane to the east of Woodhall Spa. It is open to the public for a range of recreational activities throughout the year. It is primarily pine with oak, birch and some other species around the fringes. It is bordered to the east by [[Kirkby Moor Nature Reserve]] and to the south by the former RAF Woodhall Spa, which has recently been purchased by the [[Lincolnshire Wildlife Trust]] soon to become a nature reserve.\n\nTo the east of the village between Horncastle Road and Kirkby Lane lie Kirkby and Roughton Moors. Once open heathland, these are now almost all wooded, with parts owned by the [[Lincolnshire Wildlife Trust]] and managed as two nature reserves: [[Kirkby Moor Nature Reserve]] and [[Roughton Moor Wood Nature Reserve]]. Both are open to the public and can be accessed from either Kirkby Lane, Wellsyke Lane or Horncastle Road.\n\nThere are more areas of woodland towards [[Horncastle, Lincolnshire|Horncastle]] to the north of the Viking Way/Spa Trail: Highhall Wood is private but with a permissive access footpath through it; White Hall Wood is open to the public and Thornton Wood is private.\n\n===The National Golf Centre===\n{{main|Woodhall Spa Golf Club}}\nThe first nine-hole golf course was opened in Woodhall Spa in 1890, but only survived until 1895 when the land was required for building.<ref name=CA/> A new site was found and another nine-hole [[golf course]] was laid out, but by 1902 it became clear that the golf course would have to find another new home as the land was again required for the expansion of the spa town.<ref name=CA/>\n\nLocal landowner Stafford Vere Hotchkin, offered a sandy tract of land off the Horncastle Road to build an 18-hole course. The course was designed by [[Harry Vardon]] and was formally opened for play on 24 April 1905. It was remodelled in 1911 by Harry Colt, and again by Hotchkin himself in the 1920s.<ref name=Golf>{{cite web|title=Golf Club|url=http://www.woodhallspa.org/club_woodhallgolf.html|publisher=Woodhall Spa Website|accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nWomersley House was built by the Hotchkin family, which was instrumental in the development of the adjoining Hotchkin Golf Course\u2014now the headquarters of the [[English Golf Union]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 5: Properties worth more than \u00a31 million for sale in Lincolnshire|url=http://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/5-properties-worth-1-million-sale-lincolnshire/story-19854910-detail/story.html|website=lincolnshirelive.co.uk|publisher=Lincolnshire Echo|accessdate=11 December 2016}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> who bought the course in 1995 to set up a [[National Golf Centre]].<ref name=Golf/><ref name=CNGU>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Golf Club|url=http://www.woodhallspagolf.com/?splash=1|publisher=2011 Council of National Golf Unions|accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref> A second course, \"The Bracken\", opened for play in 1998 alongside the original course, now named \"the Hotchkin\".<ref name=CNGU/> The [[St Andrews Trophy]] was held at the golf course in 1996.<!--{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}No citation needed; it's on the wikipage to which it's linked.-->\n\nMost recently, it was voted 20th best course in the world by ''[[Today's Golfer]]'' magazine in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa |url=http://admin.todaysgolfer.co.uk/Golf/courses/Top-100-Golf-Courses-in-the-World/The-Worlds-Top-100-20---11/Woodhall-Spa-Golf-Club/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120701102850/http://admin.todaysgolfer.co.uk/Golf/courses/Top-100-Golf-Courses-in-the-World/The-Worlds-Top-100-20---11/Woodhall-Spa-Golf-Club/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=1 July 2012 |publisher=Today's Golfer Magazine |accessdate=27 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Footpaths and Walking===\nThe [[Viking Way]] is a {{convert|147|mi|km}} [[long-distance footpath]] which passes through Woodhall Spa en route between the [[Humber Bridge]] and [[Oakham]] in [[Rutland]].<ref name=Vik>{{cite web|title=Viking Way|url=http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_id=504|publisher=Long Distance Walkers Association|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Spa Trail - geograph.org.uk - 1198159.jpg|thumb|180px|right|Spa Trail]]\nThe Spa Trail runs for {{convert|3.3|mi|km}} along the [[Viking Way]] and the old [[Horncastle Railway]] between Sandy Lane near Woodhall Spa and Thornton Lodge near Horncastle.<ref name=Vik/><ref>{{cite web|title=Visit Lincolnshire|url=http://www.visitlincolnshire.com/site/things-to-do/activities/the-spa-trail-p341081|work=The Spa Trail|publisher=Lincolnshire County Council|accessdate=26 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725215457/http://www.visitlincolnshire.com/site/things-to-do/activities/the-spa-trail-p341081|archivedate=25 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> With the Viking Way it forms a continuous traffic-free footpath between Woodhall Spa and [[Horncastle, Lincolnshire|Horncastle]].\n\nThe Water Rail Way is a {{Convert|25|mi|km}} long part of the [[National Cycle Network]] that runs from [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]] to [[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]], following as closely as possible the banks of the [[River Witham]]. Between Woodhall Spa and Lincoln it consists of a tarmacked path that runs along the route of the former railway line from Boston to Lincoln. It was built and financed by [[Sustrans]] organisation, and was finally completed and opened in November 2008. It is open to all forms of non-motorised transport, forming part of [[National Cycle Network|NCN]] Route 1. Named primarily after its route and former use, the path is also named after a native but seldom-seen wading bird called the [[water rail]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Water Rail Way|url=http://www.sustrans.org.uk/sustrans-near-you/midlands/easy-rides-in-the-midlands/water-rail-way|publisher=Sustrans|accessdate=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nThe Legacy Woodhall Spa Hotel opened in 1882 as the Eagle Lodge Hotel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lincs To The Past|url=http://www.lincstothepast.com/Woodhall-Spa-Hotel-including-The-Lodge-pub--Woodhall-Spa/246360.record?pt=S|work=Woodhall Spa Hotel|publisher=Lincolnshire Archives|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref>  It was converted into a nursing home in the 1960s and reopened as a hotel in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|title=Legacy Woodhall Spa Hotel|url=http://www.legacy-hotels.co.uk/legacy-woodhall/index.php|publisher=Legacy Woodhall Spa Hotel|accessdate=27 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511213506/http://www.legacy-hotels.co.uk/legacy-woodhall/index.php|archivedate=11 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nThe Golf Hotel was originally called Clevedon House and has been a school, a club and a hotel of the same name.<ref>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:Xcf5GGuKZjwJ:www.e-lindsey.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/3C7DD823-9CC3-48F0-9194-66C3EFE9C1F7/0/woodhall_spa_conservation_area_appraisal_draft.pdf+woodhall+spa+well+collapsed&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjU-7m8sFcm55NM6F9EBXE41ErZPP8hQfATJ-m7TfEjdjQ9Bt3axe-mYkT5FOqNlX0aPQpuask3qAejS1qvNovpj8LoQGf8j9GrKYORCtc7UEKKOm6LSaTUUqPVWgCb5hdY5Szn&sig=AHIEtbTc1krGEJuLtHkPys0HjQ6k69L8MA|page= 40|publisher=Woodhall Spa Conservation Area Appraisal|accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref><ref name=Horn/>\n\nThe Royal Hydro Hotel and the attached Winter Gardens were mostly destroyed in a German air raid during [[World War II]] in August 1943, although part survived and became the Mall Hotel.<ref name=Horn>{{cite web|title=Horncastle Lincolnshire|url=http://www.horncastleuk.com/historydetail.php?id=735&cid=592&f=Horncastle|publisher=Visitor UK|accessdate=27 May 2011}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"Woodhall Spa\">{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa|url=http://www.visitlincolnshire.com/aviation/towns-and-villages/woodhall-spa-p148871|publisher=Lincolnshire County Council|accessdate=26 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725215515/http://www.visitlincolnshire.com/aviation/towns-and-villages/woodhall-spa-p148871|archivedate=25 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Petwood Hotel is so called because it was originally built at the turn of the 20th century as a house for Grace, Lady Weigall, who had it constructed in her favourite wood, her \"pet wood\". Lady Weigall turned her former home into a hotel in 1933.<ref name=Horn/>\n\nThe heyday of Woodhall Spa was recorded by a local photographer, John Wield, and many of his photographs are displayed in the [[Woodhall Spa Cottage Museum]], which was his home.<ref name=Horn/><ref>{{cite web|title=Visit Lincolnshire|url=http://www.visitlincolnshire.com/site/things-to-do/woodhall-spa-cottage-museum-p15831|work=Woodhall Spa Cottage Museum|publisher=Lincolnshire County Council|accessdate=26 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717224312/http://www.visitlincolnshire.com/site/things-to-do/woodhall-spa-cottage-museum-p15831|archivedate=17 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Churches==\n[[Saint Peter]]'s church was built in 1893,<ref name=Peter>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Heritage| url=http://www.woodhallspa.org/heritage_stpeters_church.html|publisher=Woodhall Spa Heritage|accessdate=28 April 2011}}</ref> although it was not until 1915 that it was legally designated the [[parish church]].<ref name=\"Peter\"/> The building was designed by architect [[C. Hodgson Fowler|C H Fowler]] in brick with a half-timbered bell turret, and with glass by [[James Powell and Sons|Powell's]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Pevsner, Nikolaus|author2=Harris, John|editor1-last=Antram|editor1-first=Nicholas|title=The Buildings of England: Lincolnshire|date=1989|publisher=Penguin|location=London|isbn=0 14 071027 2|page=810|edition=2nd}}</ref> Until then the little church of [[Saint Andrew]], built in 1846,<ref name=Cox>Cox, J. Charles (1916); ''Lincolnshire'' p. 343; ''Methuen & Co. Ltd.''; Retrieved 28 April 2011</ref> was the parish church, but was too small for the rapidly growing town.<ref name=\"Peter\"/>\nWoodhall Spa is now part of a group of six [[Anglican]] parishes comprising:\nWoodhall Spa and Kirkstead, [[Stixwould]], [[Horsington, Lincolnshire|Horsington]], Langton with [[Woodhall, Lincolnshire|Old Woodhall]], and [[Bucknall, Lincolnshire|Bucknall]] with [[Tupholme]].<ref name=Church>{{cite web|title=Woodhall Spa Heritage| url=http://www.woodhallspa.org/services_worship.html|publisher=Woodhall Spa Heritage|accessdate=28 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Church of [[Blessed Virgin Mary (Roman Catholic)|Our Lady]] and [[Saint Peter]],<ref name=\"Church\"/> built in 1893,<ref name=Cox/> is Woodhall Spa's [[Roman Catholic]] church.\n\n==Education==\n\nThere are two schools within Woodhall Spa; [[St Hugh's School, Woodhall Spa|St Hugh's School]],<ref>[http://www.st-hughs.lincs.sch.uk St Hugh's]</ref> a preparatory boarding school on Cromwell Avenue, and St Andrew's C of E Primary School on King Edward Crescent.\n\nSecondary schools are outside Woodhall and include [[Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School, Horncastle|Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School]] and [[Banovallum School]] in [[Horncastle, Lincolnshire|Horncastle]], and [[Gartree Community School]] in [[Tattershall]].\n\n==Twin Town==\n\n* {{flagicon|France}} [[Ro\u00e9z\u00e9-sur-Sarthe]] in [[Pays de la Loire]] which is {{circa}}{{Convert|6|mi|km}} south west of [[Le Mans]]. The charter was signed in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lincolnshire Twinning Federation|url=http://www.twinninglincs.org/Woodhall%20Spa.htm|work=Woodhall Spa|publisher=Lincolnshire Twinning Federation|accessdate=26 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217081331/http://www.twinninglincs.org/Woodhall%20Spa.htm|archivedate=17 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Notable residents ==\n<!-- NOTE - Do not add people who have no independent cited references to Woodhall association within their own Wikipedia article. If no Wikipedia article, they should have independent cited evidence of being Woodhall associated and of being well-known at least nationally, otherwise additions will not meet Wikipedia Notability standards and will be removed. Discuss additions and edits on the talk page, and add them in alphabetical order.-->\n\n* [[Air Vice-Marshal]] Allan Blackley [[CBE]]; commandant of the [[Central Flying School]] at [[RAF Scampton]] 1985&ndash;7{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n<!--* [[Jason Bradbury]]; went to St Andrews C of E Primary School Not according to his WP entry-->\n* [[Violet Dickson]] [[DBE]] (1896&ndash;1991); attended the village's Miss Lunn's High School in the early 1900s{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n* [[Flying Officer]] Ray Grayston (1918&ndash;2010); one of the last survivors of the Dambusters' raid and was flight engineer of the Lancaster that breached the Eder Dam.<ref>{{cite news|title=Flying Officer Ray Grayston|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/military-obituaries/air-force-obituaries/7647326/Flying-Officer-Ray-Grayston.html|accessdate=11 December 2016|date=28 April 2010|work=Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n* Michael Hardie [[OBE]]; [[List of Diplomats of the United Kingdom to the Gambia|High Commissioner to the Gambia]] from 1994-5<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U18989 |title=HARDIE, Michael John |work=Who's Who 2009 |publisher=A & C Black |year=2008 |accessdate=24 July 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Leonard Cheshire]] {{postnominals|country=GBR|sep=,|VC|OM|DSO|DFC}} (1917\u20131992); lived here during his time as Officer Commanding [[No. 617 Squadron RAF|No. 617 Squadron]] (November 1943\u2013July 1944) and was created a [[life peer]] as ''Baron Cheshire, of Woodhall in the County of Lincolnshire''<ref name=\"nyt1992\">\"Lord Cheshire, World War II Hero Who Founded Homes for Sick, 74,\" ''The New York Times.'' 2 August 1992.</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52608 |date=22 July 1991 |page=11147}}</ref> in 1991\n* [[John Hartley (cricketer)|John Hartley]] (1874&ndash;1963); Test cricketer who died in Woodhall Spa\n*[[Monica Irimia]] Cheeky Girl and musician currently resides in Woodhall Spa{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n* [[Ursula Niebuhr]] (1907&ndash;1997); Theologian{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n* [[Steve Plater]] (b.1972); motorcyclist\n* [[David Tarttelin]] (b.1929); painter who, as a child was evacuated to Woodhall Spa during the Second World War\n* [[Adrian Tchaikovsky]]; Author<ref>{{cite web|title=Adrian Tchaikovsky|url=http://www.panmacmillan.com/search?searchtext=Adrian+Tchaikovsky&searchmode=anyword|publisher=Pan Macmillan|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Robert Webb (actor)|Robert Webb]] (b.1972); actor, comedian and writer who grew up in Woodhall Spa.<ref>{{cite news|title=Comedy star goes back to School|url=http://www.horncastlenews.co.uk/news/comedy-star-goes-back-to-school-1-842598|accessdate=11 December 2016|work=Horncastle News|date=14 April 2006}}</ref>\n* Sir [[Archibald Weigall]] {{postnominals|country=GBR|sep=,|KCMG}} Baronet Weigall of Woodhall Spa (1874&ndash;1952); Governor of South Australia<ref name=Horn/>\n* [[David Wigley]] (b.1981); cricketer{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n* [[Willie Hamilton]] (1917&ndash;2000); former Labour MP and noted republican<ref>{{cite news|last1=Roth|first1=Andrew|title=Willie Hamilton Obituary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2000/jan/27/guardianobituaries|accessdate=11 December 2016|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Woodhall Spa- Tower on the Moor (geograph 3089843).jpg|Tower-on-the-Moor\nFile:Spa baths - geograph.org.uk - 1198182.jpg|The derelict Spa Baths in 2009\nFile:The Golf Hotel, Woodhall Spa - geograph.org.uk - 549435.jpg|The Golf Hotel\nFile:The Cottage Museum, Woodhall Spa - geograph.org.uk - 949455.jpg|The Cottage Museum, Woodhall Spa\nFile:Kirkstead Abbey ruin - geograph.org.uk - 694757.jpg|[[Kirkstead Abbey]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of spa towns in the United Kingdom]]\n* [https://archive.is/20130829131252/http://www.lincolnshireinfocus.co.uk/articles/15082013-Woodhall_Spa/ Article on the history of Woodhall Spa]\n* [[Kirkstead]]\n** [[Kirkstead Abbey]]\n** [[St Leonard's Without]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Woodhall Spa}}\n* {{PastScape|mnumber=1432038 |mname=Woodhall Spa Airfield|accessdate=}}\n* [http://lincoln.ourchurchweb.org.uk/woodhallspa/ Woodhall Spa Group of Parishes]\n* [http://www.woodhallspa.org Woodhall Spa Community Website]\n* [http://www.lincolnshirepga.org.uk/woodhall-spa.aspx Lincolnshire PGA - Woodhall Spa Golf Glub]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://www.thekinemainthewoods.co.uk The Kinema In The Woods Official website]\n* [http://www.aquasante.co.uk/home.htm Aqua Sante Spa]\n* [http://www.WoodhallSpaManor.com Woodhall Spa Manor]\n* [http://www.catholicchurchwoodhallspa.org Our Lady and St Peter Catholic Church website]\n* [http://www.st-hughs.lincs.sch.uk St. Hugh's school Website]\n\n{{Portal bar|England|United Kingdom}}\n{{Lincolnshire|state=collapsed}}\n{{East Lindsey (district)|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:East Lindsey District]]\n[[Category:Spa towns in England]]\n", "name_user": "Edwin of Northumbria", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRailways:Fixed citation error.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woodhall_Spa"}
{"title_page": "Mow Cop", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n |country = England\n |official_name = Mow Cop\n |map_type=Cheshire\n |coordinates = {{coord|53.112973|-2.217582|display=inline,title}}\n |civil_parish1 = [[Kidsgrove]]\n |civil_parish = [[Odd Rode]]\n |unitary_england = [[Cheshire East]]\n |shire_district3 = [[Newcastle-under-Lyme (borough)|Newcastle-under-Lyme]]\n |lieutenancy_england= [[Cheshire]]\n |shire_county3 = [[Staffordshire]]\n |region1 = West Midlands \n |region = North West England\n |static_image_name =        Mow_Cop_folly_angle_2.jpg\n |static_image_caption =     Mow Cop Castle\n |static_image_alt =         Mow Cop Castle\n |constituency_westminster=[[Congleton (UK Parliament constituency)|Congleton]]\n |constituency_westminster1=[[Staffordshire Moorlands (UK Parliament constituency)|Staffordshire Moorlands]]\n |post_town= STOKE-ON-TRENT\n |postcode_district= ST7\n |postcode_area = ST\n |dial_code = 01782\n |os_grid_reference = SJ855573}}\n'''Mow Cop''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|a\u028a|\u02c8|k|\u0252|p}} is a village on the [[Cheshire]]\u2013[[Staffordshire]] border, divided between the [[North West England|North West]] and [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]] regions of England. It is {{convert|24|mi}} south of Manchester and {{convert|6|mi}} north of Stoke-on-Trent, on a steep hill of the same name rising up to {{convert|335|m}} above sea level.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mow Cop - Trig Point |url=http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?rf=2826|publisher=Hill Bagging|access-date=29 April 2016}}</ref> The village is among the westernmost hills of the [[Staffordshire Moorlands]], with the [[Cheshire Plain]] directly to the west. For population details taken at the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 census]], see [[Kidsgrove]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe {{convert|335|m|adj=on}} hill on which the village lies upon is a [[moorland]] ridge composed of [[sandstone]] and [[Millstone Grit]] rising eastwards above the Cheshire Plain. It is at the western edge of the Staffordshire Moorlands, forming the upland fringe of the southern [[Pennines]], most of which are in the [[Peak District|Peak District National Park]] to the east.<ref>{{cite web |title=Potteries and Churnet Valley|url=http://www.snh.org.uk/wwo/sharinggoodpractice/CCI/cci/westmidlands/064.htm|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|access-date=3 May 2016 |archivedate=2 June 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602021346/http://www.snh.org.uk/wwo/sharinggoodpractice/CCI/cci/westmidlands/064.htm}}</ref> On a clear day, the hill offers views extending to the [[West Pennine Moors]], Welsh mountains (including [[Snowdonia]]), [[Shropshire Hills]] and [[Cannock Chase]].\n\n==History==\nThe name is first recorded as ''Mowel'' around 1270 AD, and is believed to derive from either the [[Anglo-Saxon language|Anglo-Saxon]] ''M\u016bga-hyll'', meaning \"heap-hill\", with ''copp'' = \"head\" added later, or the [[Common Celtic]] ancestor of Welsh ''moel'' (= hill), with Anglo-Saxon ''copp'' added later.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kent |first=Jeff |author-link1=Jeff Kent (author) |date=2013 |title=Staffordshire's 1,000-Foot Peaks |publisher=Witan Books |isbn=978-0-9927505-0-3 }}</ref>\n\nAt the village's summit, men once quarried stone to make into [[querns]], used since the [[Iron Age]] for milling corn; this trade ended during the [[Victorian period]]. The village also has a long history of coal mining. A {{convert|65|ft|adj=on}} rock feature called the Old Man O'Mow in one of the quarried areas is believed to be the site of an ancient cairn.\n\nThe village was served by a [[Mow Cop and Scholar Green railway station|railway station]], opened by the [[North Staffordshire Railway]] on 9 October 1848 and closed in 1964.\n\n==The Castle==\nThe most dominant feature of the village is [[Mow Cop Castle]], a [[folly]] of a ruined castle at the summit of the hill, built in 1754. Both Mow Cop Castle and the Old Man O'Mow are under the management of the [[National Trust]], and on the route of the [[Cheshire Gritstone Trail]], a long-distance walking route.\n\n==Birthplace of Primitive Methodism==\nMow Cop is noteworthy as the birthplace of the [[Primitive Methodism|Primitive Methodist]] movement. Starting in 1800, [[Hugh Bourne]] from [[Stoke-on-Trent]] and [[William Clowes (Primitive Methodist)|William Clowes]] from [[Burslem]] began holding open-air [[prayer meeting]]s. On 31 May 1807, a large 14-hour [[camp meeting]] was held, leading to the founding of the Primitive Methodist Church in 1810. These camp meetings became a regular feature at Mow Cop, being held to celebrate the 100th, 150th and 200th [[anniversary|anniversaries]] of the first camp.<ref>{{cite book|last=Farndale|first=W. E.|title=The Secret of Mow Cop: A New Appraisal of the Origins of Primitive Methodism|publisher=Epworth Press|location=London|year=1950}}</ref>\n\n==In the arts==\nThe village and castle are featured prominently in the 1973 novel ''[[Red Shift (novel)|Red Shift]],'' by [[Alan Garner]]. This novel was filmed by the BBC in the 1970s, and later released in a restored HD DVD in 2014.  Mow Cop and its castle also feature in Alan Garner's 1966 photo-story book for children, ''The Old Man of Mow''.\n\nThe castle has also been a magnet for artists, and can be seen in everything from local watercolour and oil paintings and postcards, to ceramics made in the nearby Potteries. An engraving of it also featured on a Royal Mail stamp book in 1981.\n\n==Running & Cycling==\nSince the late 20th century, Mow Cop has been known for its Killer Mile, a one-mile running race from the railway level crossing on the western side of the hill up to the castle. The race was first organized in the early 1980s by John Britton.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mowcop.info/killermile/killermile.htm |title=Killer Mile |website=www.mowcop.info |publisher=Mow Cop Residents Association |access-date=30 June 2015}}</ref> The climb is also well known among local cyclists and features in the ''100 Greatest Cycling Climbs in Britain''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Warren|first1=Simon|title=100 greatest cycling climbs: A road cyclist's guide to Britain's hills|date=2010|publisher=Frances Lincoln|location=London|isbn=9780711231207}}</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n<!--include only those persons with WP articles that support residency; alphabetical order by surname, please-->\n* [[Ralph Barlow]] (1876 in Mow Cop \u2013 1897), footballer who played for [[Port Vale F.C.|Burslem Port Vale]] in the mid-1890s.\n* [[Emmanuel Foster]] (1921\u20131965), English footballer, played for Mow Cop, [[Stoke City F.C.]] and [[Stafford Rangers F.C.]]\n* [[Alan Jones (footballer born 1945)|Alan Jones]] (born 1945), former director of [[Port Vale F.C.]]\n* [[Jack Simcock]] (1929\u20132012), artist, known for \"a long series of bleak, sombre oils on board\" of the Mow Cop area where he lived.\n* [[Allen Tankard|Allen John Tankard]] (born 1969), English former footballer who played 519 league games, 275 for Port Vale. After retiring he worked in Mow Cop at a minibus and coach hire company which he now co-owns.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\nThe following references are listed in the two books by Philip R. Leese:\n*{{cite book |last=Deardon |first=John |title=Tale of the Backbone: Journey Along the Watershed of England |publisher=Book Guild |date=1986 |isbn=0863321380}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Garner |first1=Alan |last2=Hill |first2=Roger |title=The Old Man of Mow |publisher=Collins |date=1966 |asin=B005OH72RS}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Harper |first=W. J. |title=Mow Cop and its Slopes: A Short History |publisher=The Local Herald |ASIN=B004X2F04C |date=1907}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Hoskins |first1=W. G. |last2=Grigson |first2=Geoffrey |title=Chilterns to Black Country |series=About Britain |volume=5 |publisher=Collins |date=1951 |asin=B0006D9DKY}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Kennedy |editor-first=J. |title=Biddulph (\"By the Diggings\"): A Local History |publisher=Dept. of Adult Education, Keele University  |date=1980 |asin=B001OK2LSE}}\n*{{cite book |last=Rowley |first=F. |title=Rowley's Photographic Centenary Souvenirs: Historic Mow Cop and Early Primitive Methodism |publisher=F. Rowley |location=Biddulph |date=c. 1907}}\n*{{cite book |last=Simcock |first=J. |title=Simcock, Mow Cop |publisher=self-published |date=1975}}\n*{{cite book |last=Walford |first=John |title=Memoirs of the Life and Labours of the Late Venerable Hugh Bourne: By a Member of the Bourne Family |isbn=110802498X |orig-year=1854 |date=2011 |publisher=Cambridge University Press}}\n*{{cite book |first1=Arthur |last1=Wilkes |first2=Joseph |last2=Lovatt  |title=Mow Cop and the Camp Meeting Movement: Sketches of Primitive Methodism  |date=1942 |publisher=Orphans' Printing Press Ltd |asin=B002A8PCY4}}\n*{{cite book |last=Leese |first=Philip R. |title=Mow Cop: A Working Village |publisher=Churnet Valley Books |date=2010 |isbn=9781904546726}} Covers quarrying, coal mining, fustian, farming, shops and small businesses, and public houses.\n*{{cite book |last=Leese |first=Philip R. |title=Mow Cop: Living on the Hill |publisher=Churnet Valley Books |date=2011 |isbn=9781904546764}} Covers social life, literary references to the hill, the Castle, the Mow Cop Giantess (Hannah Dale), Primitive Methodism, chapels, churches, schools, recreation, wartime reminiscences, and the artist Jack Simcock.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mow Cop}}\n{{Portal|Cheshire}}\n*[http://viewfinderpanoramas.org/panoramas/ENG/MOWCOP.GIF Mow Cop Computer-generated summit panoramas]\n*[http://www.mowcop.info/ History of Mow Cop]\n\n{{Cheshire}}\n{{Staffordshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Villages in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme]]\n[[Category:Towns and villages of the Peak District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n |country = England\n |official_name = Mow Cop\n |map_type=Cheshire\n |coordinates = {{coord|53.112973|-2.217582|display=inline,title}}\n |civil_parish1 = [[Kidsgrove]]\n |civil_parish = [[Odd Rode]]\n |unitary_england = [[Cheshire East]]\n |shire_district3 = [[Newcastle-under-Lyme (borough)|Newcastle-under-Lyme]]\n |lieutenancy_england= [[Cheshire]]\n |shire_county3 = [[Staffordshire]]\n |region1 = West Midlands \n |region = North West England\n |static_image_name =        Mow_Cop_folly_angle_2.jpg\n |static_image_caption =     Mow Cop Castle\n |static_image_alt =         Mow Cop Castle\n |constituency_westminster=[[Congleton (UK Parliament constituency)|Congleton]]\n |constituency_westminster1=[[Staffordshire Moorlands (UK Parliament constituency)|Staffordshire Moorlands]]\n |post_town= STOKE-ON-TRENT\n |postcode_district= ST7\n |postcode_area = ST\n |dial_code = 01782\n |os_grid_reference = SJ855573}}\n'''Mow Cop''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|a\u028a|\u02c8|k|\u0252|p}} is a village on the [[Cheshire]]\u2013[[Staffordshire]] border, divided between the [[North West England|North West]] and [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]] regions of England. It is {{convert|24|mi}} south of Manchester and {{convert|6|mi}} north of Stoke-on-Trent, on a steep hill of the same name rising up to {{convert|335|m}} above sea level.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mow Cop - Trig Point |url=http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?rf=2826|publisher=Hill Bagging|access-date=29 April 2016}}</ref> The village is among the westernmost hills of the [[Staffordshire Moorlands]], with the [[Cheshire Plain]] directly to the west. For population details taken at the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 census]], see [[Kidsgrove]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe {{convert|335|m|adj=on}} hill on which the village lies upon is a [[moorland]] ridge composed of [[sandstone]] and [[Millstone Grit]] rising eastwards above the Cheshire Plain. It is at the western edge of the Staffordshire Moorlands, forming the upland fringe of the southern [[Pennines]], most of which are in the [[Peak District|Peak District National Park]] to the east.<ref>{{cite web |title=Potteries and Churnet Valley|url=http://www.snh.org.uk/wwo/sharinggoodpractice/CCI/cci/westmidlands/064.htm|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|access-date=3 May 2016 |archivedate=2 June 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602021346/http://www.snh.org.uk/wwo/sharinggoodpractice/CCI/cci/westmidlands/064.htm}}</ref> On a clear day, the hill offers views extending to the [[West Pennine Moors]], Welsh mountains (including [[Snowdonia]]), [[Shropshire Hills]] and [[Cannock Chase]].\n\n==History==\nThe name is first recorded as ''Mowel'' around 1270 AD, and is believed to derive from either the [[Anglo-Saxon language|Anglo-Saxon]] ''M\u016bga-hyll'', meaning \"heap-hill\", with ''copp'' = \"head\" added later, or the [[Common Celtic]] ancestor of Welsh ''moel'' (= hill), with Anglo-Saxon ''copp'' added later.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kent |first=Jeff |author-link1=Jeff Kent (author) |date=2013 |title=Staffordshire's 1,000-Foot Peaks |publisher=Witan Books |isbn=978-0-9927505-0-3 }}</ref>\n\nAt the village's summit, men once quarried stone to make into [[querns]], used since the [[Iron Age]] for milling corn; this trade ended during the [[Victorian period]]. The village also has a long history of coal mining. A {{convert|65|ft|adj=on}} rock feature called the Old Man O'Mow in one of the quarried areas is believed to be the site of an ancient cairn.\n\nThe village was served by a [[Mow Cop and Scholar Green railway station|railway station]], opened by the [[North Staffordshire Railway]] on 9 October 1848 and closed in 1964.\n\n==The Castle==\nThe most dominant feature of the village is [[Mow Cop Castle]], a [[folly]] of a ruined castle at the summit of the hill, built in 1754. Both Mow Cop Castle and the Old Man O'Mow are under the management of the [[National Trust]], and on the route of the [[Cheshire Gritstone Trail]], a long-distance walking route.\n\n==Birthplace of Primitive Methodism==\nMow Cop is noteworthy as the birthplace of the [[Primitive Methodism|Primitive Methodist]] movement. Starting in 1800, [[Hugh Bourne]] from [[Stoke-on-Trent]] and [[William Clowes (Primitive Methodist)|William Clowes]] from [[Burslem]] began holding open-air [[prayer meeting]]s. On 31 May 1807, a large 14-hour [[camp meeting]] was held, leading to the founding of the Primitive Methodist Church in 1810. These camp meetings became a regular feature at Mow Cop, being held to celebrate the 100th, 150th and 200th [[anniversary|anniversaries]] of the first camp.<ref>{{cite book|last=Farndale|first=W. E.|title=The Secret of Mow Cop: A New Appraisal of the Origins of Primitive Methodism|publisher=Epworth Press|location=London|year=1950}}</ref>\n\n==In the arts==\nThe village and castle are featured prominently in the 1973 novel ''[[Red Shift (novel)|Red Shift]],'' by [[Alan Garner]]. This novel was filmed by the BBC in the 1970s, and later released in a restored HD DVD in 2014.  Mow Cop and its castle also feature in Alan Garner's 1966 photo-story book for children, ''The Old Man of Mow''.\n\nThe castle has also been a magnet for artists, and can be seen in everything from local watercolour and oil paintings and postcards, to ceramics made in the nearby Potteries. An engraving of it also featured on a Royal Mail stamp book in 1981.\n\n==Cycling==\nSince the late 20th century, Mow Cop has been known for its Killer Mile, a one-mile road-cycling race from the railway level crossing on the western side of the hill up to the castle. The race was first organized in the early 1980s by John Britton.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mowcop.info/killermile/killermile.htm |title=Killer Mile |website=www.mowcop.info |publisher=Mow Cop Residents Association |access-date=30 June 2015}}</ref> The climb is also well known among local cyclists and features in the ''100 Greatest Cycling Climbs in Britain''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Warren|first1=Simon|title=100 greatest cycling climbs: A road cyclist's guide to Britain's hills|date=2010|publisher=Frances Lincoln|location=London|isbn=9780711231207}}</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n<!--include only those persons with WP articles that support residency; alphabetical order by surname, please-->\n* [[Ralph Barlow]] (1876 in Mow Cop \u2013 1897), footballer who played for [[Port Vale F.C.|Burslem Port Vale]] in the mid-1890s.\n* [[Emmanuel Foster]] (1921\u20131965), English footballer, played for Mow Cop, [[Stoke City F.C.]] and [[Stafford Rangers F.C.]]\n* [[Alan Jones (footballer born 1945)|Alan Jones]] (born 1945), former director of [[Port Vale F.C.]]\n* [[Jack Simcock]] (1929\u20132012), artist, known for \"a long series of bleak, sombre oils on board\" of the Mow Cop area where he lived.\n* [[Allen Tankard|Allen John Tankard]] (born 1969), English former footballer who played 519 league games, 275 for Port Vale. After retiring he worked in Mow Cop at a minibus and coach hire company which he now co-owns.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\nThe following references are listed in the two books by Philip R. Leese:\n*{{cite book |last=Deardon |first=John |title=Tale of the Backbone: Journey Along the Watershed of England |publisher=Book Guild |date=1986 |isbn=0863321380}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Garner |first1=Alan |last2=Hill |first2=Roger |title=The Old Man of Mow |publisher=Collins |date=1966 |asin=B005OH72RS}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Harper |first=W. J. |title=Mow Cop and its Slopes: A Short History |publisher=The Local Herald |ASIN=B004X2F04C |date=1907}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Hoskins |first1=W. G. |last2=Grigson |first2=Geoffrey |title=Chilterns to Black Country |series=About Britain |volume=5 |publisher=Collins |date=1951 |asin=B0006D9DKY}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Kennedy |editor-first=J. |title=Biddulph (\"By the Diggings\"): A Local History |publisher=Dept. of Adult Education, Keele University  |date=19